{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048150,"nonce":"F9qQ+LOrQZv8M7oHnGclpjj4+5I=","title":"Typing of scalar derivatives of state variables","message":"[Imported from GitHub #11] (created 2024-02-17T16:35:19Z)\n\n`feedbax.dynamics.AbstractDynamicalSystem` is a generic of `StateT`. Each subclass must define a vector field that returns the time derivatives of each array in a state PyTree.\n\n```python\ndef vector_field(\n    self, \n    t: float, \n    state: StateT, \n    input: PyTree[Array],  \n) -\u003e StateT:\n    \"\"\"Returns the time derivatives of the system's states.\"\"\"\n    ...\n```\n\nThe return type `StateT` is more or less correct: the return value will have the same PyTree structure as `state`, and -- because the time derivative is scalar -- the same array shapes as well. \n\nThis seems fine to me, but perhaps there is a better way to make it explicit when we are passing around derivatives.","files":null}]}